item.title: MSI Reveals Laptops With RTX 50-Series GPUs, Including Norse Dragon-Themed Model
item.content:encoded:
https://www.gamespot.com/articles/msi-reveals-laptops-with-rtx-50-series-gpus-including-norse-dragon-themed-model/1100-6528705/?ftag=CAD-01-10abi2f

GameSpot may receive revenue from affiliate and advertising partnerships for sharing this content and from purchases through links.

Coinciding with Nvidia's GeForce RTX 50-series GPU reveal at CES 2025, PC hardware company MSI has announced a slew of new gaming laptops running on the laptop versions of Nvidia's next-generation GPUs.

The flagship model is the Titan 18 HX Dragon Edition Norse Myth, which comes in multiple hardware configurations, the most powerful of which sports a GeForce RTX 5090 GPU, Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX CPU, and up to 96GB of DDR5 RAM. An RTX 5080 model will also be available. The 18-inch laptop features a 4K UHD MiniLED display with a 120Hz refresh rate and a unique case sporting a hand-drawn dragon illustration and Nordic runes.

In addition to the Dragon Edition Nose Myth laptop, there will also be standard edition Titan 18 HX models that ditch the fantasy aesthetics but feature the same powerful hardware options. MSI says these models all feature a 270 Watt system power, putting it on par with many desktop builds.

The rest of MSI's new RTX 50-series laptop lineup includes the Intel-based Raider 18 HX, Stealth 18 HX, Vector 17 HX AI, and Vector 16 HX AI models, and the AMD-based Raider A18 HX, Vector A18 HX, and Stealth A16 AI+. Each of the laptops is equipped with an Nvidia GeForce RTX 5090, 5080, or 5070 Ti mobile GPUs and coupled with the latest Intel Core Ultra Series 2, AMD Ryzen 9 9000, or Ryzen 3000 AI Series CPUs. The hardware enables these laptops to take advantage of the 50-series various rending and AI features, including Nvidia's new DLSS 4 upcaling technology, which promises to increase rendering performance and gameplay smoothness without requiring as much hardware horsepower.

MSI Gaming Laptops with Nvidia RTX 50-series GPUs

Titan 18 HX 18-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX
  • GPU: GeForce 5090 Laptop GPU with 24GB GDDR7 or GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Raider 18 HX 18-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX
  • GPU: GeForce 5090 Laptop GPU with 24GB GDDR7 or GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Raider A18 HX 18-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: AMD Ryzen 9 9955HX3D
  • GPU: GeForce 5090 Laptop GPU with 24GB GDDR7 or GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Vector A18 HX 18-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: AMD Ryzen 9 9955HX or AMD Ryzen 9 8945HX
  • GPU: GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7 or GeForce 5070 Ti Laptop GPU with 12GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Vector 17 HX AI 17-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX
  • GPU: GeForce 5090 Laptop GPU with 24GB GDDR7, GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7, or GeForce 5070 Ti Laptop GPU with 12GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Vector 16 HX AI 16-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX or Intel Core Ultra 7 255HX
  • GPU: GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7 or GeForce 5070 Ti Laptop GPU with 12GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Stealth 18 HX AI 18-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX
  • GPU: GeForce 5090 Laptop GPU with 24GB GDDR7, GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7, or GeForce 5070 Ti Laptop GPU with 12GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 96GB

Stealth A16 AI+ 16-inch gaming laptop

  • CPU: AMD Ryzen AI 9 HX 370
  • GPU: GeForce 5090 Laptop GPU with 24GB GDDR7, GeForce 5080 Laptop GPU with 16GB GDDR7, or GeForce 5070 Ti Laptop GPU with 12GB GDDR7
  • Memory: Up to 64GB2

MSI will also launch new models to its Crosshair and Pulse laptop lines featuring the GeForce RTX 5070.

MSI has not revealed prices or release dates for these new laptops, but considering Nvidia says the first laptops with GeForce RTX 50-series GPUs are launching in March, we would assume these MSI models will launch around then.

item.title: WoW Will Add New NPC Honoring The Remarkable Life Of Ibelin's Mats Steen
item.content:encoded:
https://www.gamespot.com/articles/wow-will-add-new-npc-honoring-the-remarkable-life-of-ibelins-mats-steen/1100-6528722/?ftag=CAD-01-10abi2f

GameSpot may receive revenue from affiliate and advertising partnerships for sharing this content and from purchases through links.

World of Warcraft continues to pay tribute to Mats "Ibelin" Steen, the subject of the recent Netflix documentary The Remarkable Life of Ibelin, this time transforming Steen's character into a full-fledged NPC.

As spotted by Wowhead, dataminers have discovered an NPC by the name of Lord Ibelin Redmoore on the public test realm for the MMORPG's upcoming 11.1 update. The NPC's appearance matches Ibelin's look in the documentary, though it's currently unclear where players will be able to find Ibelin in-game or what he might have to say should players interact with him.

Steen suffered from Duchenne muscular dystrophy and played WoW as a means of socializing and connecting with others. His character Ibelin, who he often roleplayed as, labeled himself as a private investigator and would use his in-game job title as a means to strike up conversation.

It's not the first time Blizzard has paid tribute to Steen, who passed away in 2014. He is also honored in-game with a gravestone in Elwynn Forest. Blizzard more recently offered the Reven Pack, a bundle of cosmetics (including an adorable fox in a detective hat) inspired by Steen. All of the proceeds from the Reven Pack went to support the charity CureDuchenne.

In GameSpot's The Remarkable Life of Ibelin review, we called the documentary (much of which is actually an animated film using WoW's game engine) a "vivid rendition of a virtual life" and "a powerful real-life story on the positive impact gaming can have on people's lives."

As for what's next for Blizzard's MMO, the upcoming 11.1 update will go all-in on goblins while also introducing customizable hot rods for players to drive and drift their way through the game's new Undermine zone. Blizzard recently announced as part of a Warcraft 30th anniversary steam that WoW will also finally be getting player housing, though players will have to wait until the game's next expansion, Midnight, for the highly anticipated feature.

item.title: Palworld Developer Launches New Game On Switch In Middle Of Nintendo Lawsuit
item.content:encoded:
https://www.gamespot.com/articles/palworld-developer-launches-new-game-on-switch-in-middle-of-nintendo-lawsuit/1100-6528719/?ftag=CAD-01-10abi2f

GameSpot may receive revenue from affiliate and advertising partnerships for sharing this content and from purchases through links.

Palworld developer Pocketpair has launched a new game on Nintendo Switch despite the fact that it's currently being sued by The Pokemon Company and Nintendo.

The game is called Overdungeon, which combines card game, tower defense, and roguelike elements. It has real-time gameplay with cards featuring various animals like cats, dogs, and alpacas. It was first released in 2019 for PC before its surprise launch on Switch today, January 9.

The Pokemon Company sued Pocketpair last year, alleging that the Pocketpair engaged in infringement on The Pokemon Company's patents. Pocketpair revealed that the three Japanese patents were centered around the mechanics of throwing balls at creatures to catch them, riding characters in the game, and shooting at targets.

In December, Pocketpair removed the balls, called Pal Spheres, that the creatures come out from when the spheres are thrown. Instead, the creatures just appear alongside the player when summoned.

The status of the lawsuit is still pending, and it's unclear how it impacts the two companies' relationship. However, it seems like it won't stop Pocketpair from releasing games on Nintendo's platform.

item.title: Ubisoft Refuses To Comment On Tencent Rumors But Says It's Exploring Options To Maximize Value
item.content:encoded:
https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ubisoft-refuses-to-comment-on-tencent-rumors-but-says-its-exploring-options-to-maximize-value/1100-6528718/?ftag=CAD-01-10abi2f

GameSpot may receive revenue from affiliate and advertising partnerships for sharing this content and from purchases through links.

As part its delay of Assassin's Creed Shadows, Ubisoft has announced that it's putting plans in place to pursue "various transformational strategic and capitalistic options" to help put itself in the best possible financial situation. Ubisoft said it has appointed an advisory team to do this.

Ubisoft said it will continue to "drive significant cost reductions" as part of this plan, though the company did not say if more layoffs are coming. Ubisoft added that it will take a "highly selective approach to investments" during this period. In total, Ubisoft said it expects to see a reduction of â‚¬200 million ($206 million USD) as part of this plan.

Looking ahead, Ubisoft said it expects Q3 FY2024-25 revenue to be less than what it originally forecast, due in part to lower-than-expected game sales during the holiday, mainly due to an underperformance of Star Wars Outlaws. The downturn is also attributed in part to the discontinuation of XDefiant.

During a conference call, Ubisoft CEO Yves Guillemot said he sees "several potential paths" for the company and its franchises going forward to maximize shareholder value. It was previously reported that Ubisoft was considering numerous different possibilities for its future, including selling to Tencent.

On the call, Ubisoft declined to comment on the report of the company potentially selling to Tencent, but management said it is "exploring different options," adding, "We can't say more."

Also during the call, management said it was "the difficult but right decision" to close XDefiant and shut down multiple studios around the world, adding that it's learned lessons from XDefiant's lack of success in the market.
